title: here's why it's so hard to put a computer into SPACE - NASA HPE Spacebourne 2
description:
Thanks KIOXIA for sponsoring today‚Äôs video! Check out KIOXIA's SAS and NVMe SSDs below!
https://americas.kioxia.com/en-us/business/ssd/oem/hpe.html
https://americas.kioxia.com/en-us/business/ssd/oem/hpe/pm7-enterprise-sas.html
https://americas.kioxia.com/en-us/business/ssd/client-ssd/xg8.html

It‚Äôs really hard to put a computer into space‚Ä¶ so hard in fact that laptops on the international space station are treated as effectively disposable. So when the folks at HPE wanted to put a SERVER on the ISS, people were a bit skeptical‚Ä¶ and it turned out even with the help of KIOXIA‚Äôs fast and reliable storage devices, to be harder than they thought.

Sony X95K https://amzn.to/3SpMF5y
LG G3 https://amzn.to/3S9Ag4a
Sony A80L https://amzn.to/3OcIozT

üìù TV Technology Acronym Breakdown
Most brands stick by the rule of calling the TV technology what it is in the name. LED, QLED, OLED, Mini-LED, QD-OLED, etc. But every so often you‚Äôll see a name that sounds fancy but is nothing more than a marketing name for a specific TV technology. Here are some of the most notable ones.

‚Ä¢ QLED
Hisense: ULED
Amazon: Omni QLED

‚Ä¢ Mini-LED
Samsung Neo QLED (A Mini-LED TV with a quantum dot layer over it)
LG QNED (LG‚Äôs Mini-LED technology with quantum dot)
TCL OZ Zero (TCL Mini-LED technology with quantum dot layer)

‚Ä¢ OLED
Companies will differentiate between OLED, W-OLED, and QD-OLED.
OLED in 2024 will have a 3-diode array. Sets older than 2020 may have difficulty with brightness in ultra-bright rooms
W-OLED has a 4-diode array, with one of them being a dedicated white light diode. Produced brighter overall OLED picture
QD-OLED is an OLED panel with quantum dot technology over it, producing a brighter color image and more color-accurate image.
